		INSERT INTO EssayResponses (questionResponseID, essayResponse)
		VALUES(178424272, 'The first 9 or 10 weeks of this course were the biggest headache I have ever had in a class. Hands down. I''d take Statics and Strengths again before I took this class over. Jeremy is one of the smartest professors I''ve had, and I learn more from his classes than I do from any other professor, but there is one huge problem; this class (and many of Jeremy''s classes in general) was completely unorganized, chaotic, and inconsistent. From week to week, and even day to day, we had no clue what was expected, what was due, or what the heck was going on. This class would be perfect if Jeremy would set a schedule and stick to it. We got behind instantly, and by the 6th or 7th week, we were quite a few chapters behind in the book. This led to us having to do 3 chapters at a time for a number of weeks, and created huge amounts of unneeded stress for everybody in the class. I believe throwing in the Charrette on top of everything else was a poor choice as well, and probably one of the main causes of us getting behind. I know the Charrette project applied perfectly to what we were learning, but Jeremy should have planned better for it and gotten us a chapter or two ahead so that it wouldn''t have knocked us behind when it did come up. Being behind made the syllabus and canvas change every single week, and it was impossible to keep a set homework schedule. Lots of complaints were made, and the class was going downhill fast.

Having said all of this, I will give Jeremy a huge amount of credit for what he did in about the 9th week. We basically had a coming-to-Jesus (see urbandictionary.com) in class one day, and it completely changed the tone of the class for the last few weeks. He asked what we thought of the course thus far, and we told him exactly what we thought. We spent an entire class period letting him have it, every complaint we could throw, every issue we had with the class, every thing we thought he should change, and he took us completely seriously. He completely changed the way he ran the class, laid out the rest of the semester, took all of that added stress away, and created an environment where we could actually learn instead of worrying about what curve-ball was coming next. That day made me realize how much Jeremy really cares about each student, and how much he cares that we actually learn something from his classes. He was willing to change the way he wanted to do things, in order to give us a better environment to learn in. Every class period after that day was full of discussion, and in reality, it became my favorite class to go to. The last few weeks were absolutely perfect. I truly believe that Jeremy can be one of the best professors at Weber State when he stays on schedule and stays consistent.');
	
		INSERT INTO EssayResponses (questionResponseID, essayResponse)
		VALUES(177694737, 'Brad Peterson is the best computer science teacher I have had thus far. While this is supposed to be one of the hardest CS courses, it honestly has been my favorite. Brad is really great at communicating things very clearly and making sure the material is understood, and is always available to give one on one help whenever it''s needed. I was also glad that he took time to explain things that weren''t directly relevant to our assignments, but that were useful in the computer science field in general.');
	
