		INSERT INTO EssayResponses (questionResponseID, essayResponse)
		VALUES(189821687, 'It certainly was a fun class and I value the things I do understand from the course. However, considering myself to be an above average student with above average intellect, I had a difficult time transferring what I learnt in the classroom and personal study to my tests. With a subject as fluid as Economics it is understandable that it would be difficult to teach for actual learning when there is so much to cover in the time allotted. I feel it would be beneficial for every student if there were more opportunity for Q. & A. There were some of the more difficult parts of the class such as calculations that were kind of glazed over and rushed through. I would have liked to have more instruction on that. Perhaps as a sign that the classroom is not understanding the material would be when they fail or hesitate to answer simple questions instead of answering the question for the class and expecting them to follow the path. I personally, was lost a lot of the time. I would also suggest a study guide for tests! It doesn''t have to be anything specific, just some things to search for in personal study that would help students know what would be covered on the test. With the classroom concentration on two different books, it makes it difficult to pinpoint exactly what to expect on the test. ');
	
		INSERT INTO EssayResponses (questionResponseID, essayResponse)
		VALUES(189920674, 'Professor Froerer is one of the most engaging teachers I''ve had at Weber so far. I think she has a similar teaching style as Professor Sessions - very dynamic, engaging, and exciting. My only regret is that she doesn''t teach any other economic courses, as I would have loved to have her as a future professor as well. Her stamina for teaching long three hour courses was impressive, never missing a beat and working hard to keep us learning. Bravo. ');
	
		INSERT INTO EssayResponses (questionResponseID, essayResponse)
