		INSERT INTO EssayResponses (questionResponseID, essayResponse)
		VALUES(197704629, 'Drop the heavy emphasis on coding in an obsolete language (C in UNIX v6) and explore operating systems more in their current state. Or if you are going to hold up this requirement at least mix up the grading scale with more stuff so our assignments conducted in this manner don''t decide 50% of our final grade. Get a textbook that is actually legit and discusses operating systems in a more professional manner. Go into the various concepts of operating systems in more depth and detail (CS2810 had more depth than this course). Spend lectures on exploring and discussing those concepts more than discussing the trivial details of things like LINUX, UNIX, and C.');
	
		INSERT INTO EssayResponses (questionResponseID, essayResponse)
		VALUES(197704630, 'I realize that Dr. Ball was new to Weber (almost seemed new to teaching as well but not certain) and new to teaching such a course as this, but this class was a complete disaster from day one. First day of the first week Dr. Ball didn''t even know how to use Canvas and didn''t even have the course set up on Canvas, but rather had admittedly copy and pasted Dr. Valle''s entire course layout instead (and didn''t even know that layout either). Upon discussing the use of C and UNIX v6 he also admitted not knowing C or UNIX/LINUX either. About 75% of every class was spent trying to figure out what the homework assignments required or were even about, leaving the actual course material on the back burner until the very end of the lecture. When we did finally get to discussing Operating Systems it was merely the previous night''s reading regurgitated almost word for word with little to no expansion or illustration provided. I had my faults as a student, no doubt, and I don''t expect Dr. Ball to be perfect. But this class seriously lacked in professionalism, experience, and hardly merited the time and money it requires to simply pass with a minimum required grade. As someone who is genuinely interested in operating systems I really hope you guys reevaluate this course and bring it up to speed as one of the defining upper division courses it was meant to be. ');
	
