		INSERT INTO EssayResponses (questionResponseID, essayResponse)
		VALUES(206693678, 'Suggestions for improvement:

- Create structured lessons for the first assignment or two with lectures, examples, etc. It is unacceptable to simply tell students to figure it out when a fundamentally important topic such as client/server connections is introduced for the first time in the entire CS program. Students can manage to figure it out, but they only learn the wrong way to do things. Each assignment should provide students with an industry-accepted way of accomplishing a certain task.

- Improve the process for checking off assignments. It is not only frustrating to have four weeks worth of work checked off in two minutes after a superficial examination by the instructor, but it doesnt provide the student with any usable feedback. This check-off procedure suggests that as long as it works, it is good. I believe that CS students should be taught to a much higher quality standard than this.

- The course catalog description and the actual course do not match very closely. (Note that this is technically a violation of the student rights code). I recommend going through the appropriate curriculum updating process and changing the catalog description based on advisory committee feedback, then redesigning the course to match. 

-  Stop telling students that this is a 3000 level course, so I wont be holding your hand much. I dont need/want my hand held, but I do need/want a course which has undergone a careful instructional-design process, has stated learning outcomes, has instruction which demonstrates the concepts required to meet the outcomes, has activities in which those learning outcomes are accomplished, and has a way of assessing to see if those outcomes were met. As a quick example, the first assignment in the course could have been something like the following:

Outcome:
	
Upon completion of this course, students will be able to:
Create a simple client/server web application using the Linux, Apache, MySql, PHP (LAMP) technology stack, conforming to industry-accepted practices. 

Instruction:

Lecture(s), video(s), sample code, etc. Define an explain things like AJAX, XMLHttp, POST and GET requests, JSON, etc. (None of the previous CS courses contain any instruction on these). Show the correct way to build a simple PHP backend, show how to create a simple frontend which communicates with the backend. Show/explain why it is wrong to have all the PHP, HTML, and JavaScript code inline in the same file.

Activity:

Same as your actual first LAMP assignment, except require separate frontend and backend components (no inline PHP allowed). Have more well-defined deadlines, checkpoints, and due-dates. (Should be easier to do because less time will be wasted by students since they were given actual instruction). Have them create a backend first that can be tested with a tool such as PostMan. Next, have them create the frontend. 

Assessment:

Dont only check to see if their assignment works, spend some time looking at code and giving feedback. Are industry-accepted coding practices followed? What could they have done differently, more efficiently, more securely, etc.? 
The concept of various levels of hand-holding based on the level of course (1000, 2000, 3000, 4000) is, in my opinion, a flawed way of approaching education. I completely agree that the level of rigor should be appropriate for the course level, but that equate to less instruction being provided. 3000 and 4000 level courses still need to have instruction, just on different and more challenging concepts when compared to 1000 and 2000 level courses. In a 3000 level course, it is perfectly acceptable to expect students to know concepts that were covered in prerequisite courses, but this course requires students to know many concepts that werent covered in lower-division courses. There are two obvious solutions to this problem; either teach the concepts in lower-division courses, or teach them in this class.
');
	
